{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RR3jj4sN6D5aEo4GqnK5X8","type":"tool_result","content":"   135→\n   136→```{r}\n   137→n <- 1e6\n   138→p_true <- 0.7\n   139→observed <- factor(rbinom(n = n, size = 1, prob = p_true), levels = c(0, 1))\n   140→\n   141→p_over <- p_true + 0.15\n   142→p_under <- p_true - 0.15\n   143→\n   144→abs(mean(brier_score(observed, p_true)) - mean(brier_score(observed, p_over)))\n   145→abs(mean(brier_score(observed, p_true)) - mean(brier_score(observed, p_under)))\n   146→```\n   147→\n   148→See `?brier_score()` for more information.\n   149→\n   150→\n   151→## Logarithmic score\n   152→\n   153→**Observation**: $y$, either 0 or 1\n   154→\n   155→**Forecast**: $p$, a probability that the observed outcome will be 1.\n   156→\n   157→The logarithmic score (or log score) is a strictly proper scoring rule. It is computed as the negative logarithm of the probability assigned to the observed outcome.\n   158→\n   159→\\begin{equation}\n   160→    \\text{Log score}(p, y) = - \\log(1 - |y - p|) =\n   161→    \\begin{cases}\n   162→        -\\log (p),       & \\text{if } y = 1\\\\\n   163→        -\\log (1 - p),   & \\text{if } y = 0\n   164→    \\end{cases}\n   165→\\end{equation}\n   166→\n   167→The log score penalises overconfidence more strongly than underconfidence (in probability space). Consider the following example:\n   168→\n   169→```{r}\n   170→abs(mean(logs_binary(observed, p_true)) - mean(logs_binary(observed, p_over)))\n   171→abs(mean(logs_binary(observed, p_true)) - mean(logs_binary(observed, p_under)))\n   172→```\n   173→\n   174→See `?logs_binary()` for more information.\n   175→\n   176→\n   177→---\n   178→\n   179→# Sample-based forecasts\n   180→\n   181→See a list of the default metrics for sample-based forecasts by calling `get_metrics(example_sample_continuous)`.\n   182→\n   183→This is an overview of the input and output formats for quantile forecasts:\n   184→"}]},"parent_too