{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EK3jbwb7NNqF2rXY1M46Mn","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→% Generated by roxygen2: do not edit by hand\n     2→% Please edit documentation in R/metrics-binary.R\n     3→\\name{scoring-functions-binary}\n     4→\\alias{scoring-functions-binary}\n     5→\\alias{brier_score}\n     6→\\alias{logs_binary}\n     7→\\title{Metrics for binary outcomes}\n     8→\\usage{\n     9→brier_score(observed, predicted)\n    10→\n    11→logs_binary(observed, predicted)\n    12→}\n    13→\\arguments{\n    14→\\item{observed}{A factor of length n with exactly two levels, holding\n    15→the observed values.\n    16→The highest factor level is assumed to be the reference level. This means\n    17→that \\code{predicted} represents the probability that the observed value is\n    18→equal to the highest factor level.}\n    19→\n    20→\\item{predicted}{A numeric vector of length n, holding probabilities.\n    21→Values represent the probability that the corresponding outcome is equal to\n    22→the highest level of the factor \\code{observed}.}\n    23→}\n    24→\\value{\n    25→A numeric vector of size n with the Brier scores\n    26→\n    27→A numeric vector of size n with log scores\n    28→}\n    29→\\description{\n    30→\\strong{Brier score}\n    31→\n    32→The Brier Score is the mean squared error between the probabilistic\n    33→prediction and the observed outcome. The Brier score is a proper scoring\n    34→rule. Small values are better (best is 0, the worst is 1).\n    35→\n    36→\\deqn{\n    37→  \\textrm{Brier\\_Score} = (\\textrm{prediction} - \\textrm{outcome})^2,\n    38→}{\n    39→  Brier_Score = (prediction - outcome)²,\n    40→} where \\eqn{\\textrm{outcome} \\in \\{0, 1\\}}{outcome in {0, 1}}, and\n    41→\\eqn{\\textrm{prediction} \\in [0, 1]}{prediction in [0, 1]} represents\n    42→the probability that the outcome is equal to 1.\n    43→\n    44→\\strong{Log score for binary outcomes}\n    45→\n    46→The Log Score is the negative logarithm of the probability\n    47→assigned to the observed value. It is a proper scoring rule. Small values\n    48→are better (best is zero, worst is infinity).\n    49→}\n    50→\\details{\n    51→The functions require users to provide observed values as a factor in order\n    52→to distinguish its input from the input format required for scoring point\n    53→forecasts. Internally, however, factors will be converted to numeric values.\n    54→A factor \\verb{observed = factor(c(0, 1, 1, 0, 1)} with two levels (\\code{0} and \\code{1})\n    55→would internally be coerced to a numeric vector (in this case this would\n    56→result in the numeric vector \\code{c(1, 2, 2, 1, 1)}). After subtracting 1, the\n    57→resulting vector (\\code{c(0, 1, 1, 0)} in this case) is used for internal\n    58→calculations. All predictions are assumed represent the probability that the\n    59→outcome is equal of the last/highest factor level (in this case that the\n    60→outcome is equal to 1).\n    61→\n    62→You could alternatively also provide a vector like\n    63→\\code{observed = factor(c(\"a\", \"b\", \"b\", \"a\"))} (with two levels, \\code{a} and \\code{b}),\n    64→which would result in exactly the same internal representation. Probabilities\n    65→then represent the probability that the outcome is equal to \"b\".\n    66→If you want your predictions to be probabilities that the outcome is \"a\",\n    67→then you could of course make \\code{observed} a factor with levels swapped, i.e.\n    68→\\code{observed = factor(c(\"a\", \"b\", \"b\", \"a\"), levels = c(\"b\", \"a\"))}\n    69→}\n    70→\\section{Input format}{\n    71→\\if{html}{\n    72→  \\out{<div style=\"text-align: left\">}\n    73→  \\figure{metrics-binary-point.png}{options: style=\"width:750px;max-width:100\\%;\"}\n    74→  \\out{</div><p>}\n    75→  Overview of required input format for binary and point forecasts\n    76→}\n    77→\\if{latex}{\n    78→  \\figure{metrics-binary-point.png}\n    79→}\n    80→}\n    81→\n    82→\\examples{\n    83→observed <- factor(sample(c(0, 1), size = 30, replace = TRUE))\n    84→predicted <- runif(n = 30, min = 0, max = 1)\n    85→\n    86→brier_score(observed, predicted)\n    87→logs_binary(observed, predicted)\n    88→}\n    89→\\seealso{\n    90→Other log score functions: \n    91→\\code{\\link{logs_categorical}()},\n    92→\\code{\\link{logs_sample}()}\n    93→}\n    94→\\concept{log score functions}\n    95→\\keyword{metric}\n    96→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_012s95jfAY5MQFkof1h6161G","session_id":"6bbae4ee-ba5c-4293-b37c-866678caa4c2","uuid":"98d0d202-c8c5-449e-984e-f1cba17aab2b"}
